ssians remain divided over whether the revolution arrived forcibly or inevitably and whether it was a colossally tragic or colossally generative event, but also because its social, cultural, scientific, and even moral residues remain everywhere in Putin’s Russia. Revolutionary Aftereffects looks at the ways in which 1917 has been and continues to be commemorated in Russia. Although post-Soviet Russia has emphasized its complete break with the past, this study of the memorialization and legacy of 1917 explores a fundamental continuity underlying an apparent discourse of discontinuity in post-socialist Russia. Contributors provide insight into the continuing reverberations of the revolution from a variety of disciplinary perspectives, including history and literary studies as well as heritage studies, anthropology, geography, and sociology. Collectively, these essays demonstrate the changing nature of the revolution’s memorialization in the Soviet Union and post-Soviet Russia and the ambivalence and contradictions within those narratives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Russia & the Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh  a1917 revolution.  aBoris Akunin.  aLenin.  aRussian Revolution.  aRussian architecture.  aSilent Jubilee.  aSoviet Union.  aVladimir Putin.  aanniversaries.  acentenary.  amemorialization of the past.  apost-socialist Russia.1 aAnderson, David G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaraban, Elena V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeschepper, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLipovetsky, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilina, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSwift, Megan, econtributo